How Internet Works?

1. The Main Players
To get online, you need three main components:

The Client: This is your device (phone, laptop) asking for information.

The Server: A powerful computer that "serves" content (like YouTube or Instagram). They stay turned on 24/7.

The Router: The traffic controller in your house that directs data to the right device.

2. The Journey of a Request
When you type google.com into your browser, here is what happens behind the scenes:

Step A: The Address Book (DNS)
Computers don't actually understand "https://www.google.com/url?sa=E&source=gmail&q=google.com"; they use numbers called IP Addresses (like 142.250.190.46). Your browser contacts a DNS (Domain Name System), which acts like a phonebook to translate the name you typed into the number the computer needs.

Step B: The "Packages" (Packets)
Data is too big to be sent all at once. If you download a photo, the internet breaks it into thousands of tiny pieces called Packets. Each packet has a header that says where it came from and where it’s going.

Step C: The Highway (Cables)
Most people think the internet is "in the air" (Wi-Fi), but the vast majority of it travels through physical cables.

It goes from your router to your ISP (Internet Service Provider).

From there, it travels through massive fiber-optic cables buried underground and even across the ocean floor.

Step D: Reassembly
Once those thousands of packets reach your device, your computer puts them back together in the right order—like a puzzle—and the website appears on your screen.
